```

No extra table types are needed publicly unless internal organization benefits.

## Allocation modules

Prefer type-less namespace structs:

```rust
pub struct Xmalloc;
pub struct Ialloc;
pub struct Alignalloc;
pub struct Xalignalloc;
pub struct XallocDie;
```

Because introducing allocator traits or custom owned-buffer types would exceed the evidence.

## Trait design

Use only std traits in signatures:
- `std::io::Read`
- `std::io::Write`
- `std::io::Seek`

Do not add custom project-wide traits.

## 4. Key function and method signatures

These signatures are designed to be Rust-native while preserving source behavior categories.

## `src/main.rs`

```rust
fn main();
```

Internal pattern:

```rust
fn run() -> i32;
```

Or main can directly call `Cat::run`.

## `src/cat.rs`

```rust
pub struct Cat;

#[derive(Debug)]
pub enum CatError {
    Usage(String),
    Io {
        path: Option<String>,
        source: std::io::Error,
    },
}

impl Cat {
    pub fn run<I, S>(args: I) -> i32
    where
        I: IntoIterator<Item = S>,
        S: Into<String>;

    pub fn usage(program_name: &str) -> String;

    pub fn proper_name() -> &'static str;

    pub fn next_line_num(state: &mut LineNumberState) -> String;

    pub fn simple_cat<R, W>(input: &mut R, output: &mut W) -> std::io::Result<()>
    where
        R: std::io::Read,
        W: std::io::Write;

    pub fn write_pending<W>(output: &mut W, pending: &[u8]) -> std::io::Result<()>
    where
        W: std::io::Write;

    pub fn cat<R, W>(
        input: &mut R,
        output: &mut W,
        options: &CatOptions,
        line_state: &mut LineNumberState,
    ) -> std::io::Result<()>
    where
        R: std::io::Read,
        W: std::io::Write;

    pub fn copy_cat<R, W>(
        input: &mut R,
        output: &mut W,
        options: &CatOptions,
        line_state: &mut LineNumberState,
    ) -> std::io::Result<()>
    where
        R: std::io::Read,
        W: std::io::Write;
}
```

Recommended internal helpers:

```rust
fn parse_args<I, S>(args: I) -> Result<(CatOptions, Vec<String>), CatError>
where
    I: IntoIterator<Item = S>,
    S: Into<String>;

fn render_byte(byte: u8, options: &CatOptions, out: &mut Vec<u8>);
fn should_use_simple_mode(options: &CatOptions) -> bool;
```

